LX. The common occurrences that we call rainbows Rainbows. have nothing miraculous or portentous about them, for they do not reliably portend even rain or fine weather. The obvious explanation of them is that a ray of the sun striking a hollow cloud has its point repelled and is reflected back to the sun, and that the diversified colouring is due to the mixture of clouds, fires and air. Rainbows certainly do not occur except opposite to the sun, and never except in semi-circular shape‚ and not at night time, although Aristotle does state that a rainbow has been sometimes seen at night, though he also admits that it cannot happen except on the 14th day of the lunar month.⁶ Rain- bows in winter occur chiefly when the day is drawing in after the autumna] equinox3 when the day draws out again after the vernal equinox they do not occur, nor in the longest days about the solstice‚ but they occur frequently in midwinter ‘¹3 also they are high
